{
  "unmapped_findings": [
    "The Mn/Ni ratio played a vital role towards controlling precipitation and recrystallization and accordingly, the mechanical properties.",
    "Planar slip activity, dynamic slip band refinement in conjunction with dislocation-twin interaction mechanisms were noticed in fully recrystallized austenite and thereby leading to enhanced strain hardening and ductility.",
    "Lowering Mn in Ni containing LDS reduced the processing temperature window of the alloy in two-phase region.",
    "15Mn5Ni alloy has experienced cracking beyond 50% cold reduction; hence, further reduction was not carried out on any of the chosen alloys for comparison reasons.",
    "The B2 stringer underwent concurrent deformation with austenite grains, which resulted in significant reduction in the average thickness of B2 stringer from ~8 μm to ~2 μm and eventually sheared and fragmented at higher strain.",
    "Dissolution rate of finer B2 particles was seen to be higher than that of B2 stringers.",
    "The volume fraction of annealing twins increased with the heat treatment temperature and was found to be highest in 28Mn0Ni alloy and least in 15Mn5Ni alloy at any given temperature.",
    "15Mn5Ni alloy showed much lesser recrystallization of austenite matrix and large volume fraction of secondary phase precipitation along grain boundaries forming precipitate rich zones at 1023 K.",
    "Fracture in 15Mn5Ni alloy was seemed to crack initiation-controlled with fast propagation of cracks with quasi-cleavage fracture morphology, whereas 28Mn0Ni and 28Mn5Ni exhibited dimple morphology indicating ductile failure.",
    "Inhomogeneous slip band spacing was developed in Ni containing LDS alloys, whereas Ni-free LDS (28Mn0Ni) alloy exhibited homogeneous slip band spacing under similar heat-treated conditions of HR+CR+1173 K."
  ],
